 the themes of violence, race relations, sexuality, family trauma, embodied suffering, social inequality, and power relations. The result is a dispassionate chronicle of survival, loss, caring, and hope rooted in the addicts' determination to hang on for one more day and one more "fix" through a "moral economy of sharing" that precariously balances mutual solidarity and interpersonal betrayal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDrug addictszUnited StatesxEconomic conditions. 0aDrug addictszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aHomeless personsxDrug usezUnited States. 0aMarginality, SocialzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aaddiction.  abetrayal.  abiography.  ablack and white photography.  aburglary.  adialogue.  adispassionate chronicle.  adrug abusers.  adrug and alcohol abuse.  agonzo journalism.  agripping narrative.  aheroin.  ahomeless.  ahuman survival.  ainequality.  alarceny.  alife of a drug addict.  amemoir.  aopioid epidemic.  aoverdose.  apanhandling.  arace relations.  aracism.  asan francisco drug scene.  asexuality.  asolidarity.  asuffering.  atheoretical analysis.  atrauma.  atreatment of addicts.  avicious cycle.  aviolence.1 aSchonberg, Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023088040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094331540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943315/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY